        <b><span id="titleLabel">1.5 - Cracking the code of creativity: Drawing novelty, awe, and adventure from traditional genres.</span></b>
        <table border="1" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="dateTimeLabel">Thursday, May 11, 9:30 AM - 11:00 AM</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="roomLabel">Room 404AB</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="descriptionLabel">What does it take to work <i>within</I> a popular genre but <i>outside</i> the boundaries of expectation? Is creativity really as absent from the current generation of games as many claim? This year, a number of titles answered industry critics and proved that originality in game design is limited only by a designer's intelligence, inspiration, and imagination. God of War, Project Assassins, Guitar Hero, and Spore, working within the long-established genres of action adventure, rhythm/music, and simulation confirm that faithfulness to genre, rather then limiting game design, can be fertile ground for creativity and evolution. This session invites designers to discuss how they took shop worn genres to new heights--by perfecting the wheel rather than reinventing it.</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td width="18%" class="tableCell">Moderator:</td>
                <td class="tableCell"><span id="moderatorLabel">N'Gai Croal, General Editor, Technology - Newsweek</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell">Panelists:</td>
